Reference-contexts: The separation of aerosol from molecular scattering is possible because the backscatter component from air is Doppler-broadened by the thermal velocities of the molecules, while the backscatter from more massive, slower moving particles, remains spectrally unbroadened <ref> ( Grund and Eloranta, 1991) </ref>. Such lidar system, called High Spectral Resolution Lidar (HSRL) is able to measure aerosol and cloud optical depth, as well as extinction and backscatter profiles (Kruger et al., 1993). <p> This technique, although very accurate in the determination of the aerosol extinction and backscatter profiles, remains difficult to implement since it needs a sophisticated experimental setup and a proper calibration of the lidar system <ref> (Grund and Eloranta, 1991) </ref>. The NTUA group has many years experience in designing and building Fabry-Perot interferometers for the visible and far UV region. <p> The lidar signals are detected using either dichroic beamsplitters and interference filters ( Klett and Raman techniques) or very narrow interference filters and pressure controlled dual-etalon filters <ref> (Grund and Eloranta, 1991) </ref> in the case of the HSRL technique. The lidar signals are then acquired using analog and photon counting detection systems ( Grund and Eloranta, 1991; Ansmann et al., 1992).
